I'm sure everyone here knows the kilogram is currently defined
as the amount of mass in this one particular lump of metal stored in
the outskirts of Paris.  What I didn't know is that for the past thirty
years its mass has been fluctuating relative to the duplicates made at
the same time to serve as secondary references.  Speaking precisely, of
course, its mass can't fluctuate, but that just means everything in the
universe is suffering from a gain in mass of about fifty parts in a
billion:

http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/science/nature/7084099.stm

Apparently it's not clear whether the other reference kilograms
or the Paris one is the problem.  But the General Conference on Weights
and Measures is meeting this week to discuss the problem.

--
Joseph Nebus
