The kilogram is the only SI unit that is still defined by a specific
object. They've been thinking about redefining it in terms of
fundamental constants, but it hasn't happened yet.

You can't just redefine the kilogram as the mass of a litre of water,
because the lump of metal isn't exactly that mass. There are so many
units derived from the kilogram that they can't change it now.
Apparently, the leading contender for a new definition is to use the
force generated by a known current moving through a known magnetic flux
and measured by a Watt Balance.

http://www.bipm.org/en/scientific/elec/watt_balance/

