They have to wait until they can find an easily-reproducible standard
that is actually reproducible (even if not easily).

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; I think the second is defined by
&gt; cesium, and the meter is defined by the speed of light in a vacuum;
&gt; from those (and some water) you can define the kg.
">

You would need water that is extraordinarily pure--I suspect much purer
than anything actually obtainable.  It would also have to be isotopically
pure, or at least have a well-defined isotopic composition.  And then you
would need a vessel that is measurable with your world-class standard-meter
apparatus at every conceivable point.  (If the vessel is spherical, how
do you prove it is perfectly spherical?  If it is a cube, how you prove
all panels of the cube are absolutely flat over their entire surface?)
And the vessels needs to be rigorously cleaned, with something that leaves
no residue to dissolve into or displace your water.  And the vessel needs
to not deform under the weight of the water, or the gravitational
attraction of nearby apparatuses.

They aren't going to redefine the kilogram to be something which is even
less reliable than what they already have.

Xho

